<subSubSection pageId="140" pageNumber="141" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="140.[151,1437,1335,1470]" pageId="140" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,306,1335,1362]" pageId="140" pageNumber="141">Introduction.</emphasis>
This small family includes just the single species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Cockerell" authorityName="Cockerell" box="[872,1260,1335,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Phoenicococcidae" genus="Phoenicococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marlatti">
<emphasis box="[872,1146,1336,1362]" italics="true" pageId="140" pageNumber="141">Phoenicococcus marlatti</emphasis>
Cockerell
</taxonomicName>
which feeds on date palms. Its relationships are uncertain but it is currently generally accepted that it is either close to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Giliomee" authorityYear="1967" box="[1299,1432,1371,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Diaspididae</taxonomicName>
, as found by 
<bibRefCitation author="Vea and Grimaldi" box="[287,564,1407,1434]" firstAuthor="Vea" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" pagination="23487" refId="ref212464" refString="Vea, I. M. &amp; Grimaldi, D. A. (2016) Putting scales into evolutionary time: the divergence of major scale insect lineages (Hemiptera) predates the radiation of modern angiosperm hosts. Scientific Reports, 6, 23487. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / srep 23487" type="journal article" year="2016">Vea and Grimaldi (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, or actually a member of this family. The adult males were studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stickney" firstAuthor="Stickney" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref211499" refString="Stickney, F. S. (1934) The external anatomy of the red date scale Phoenicococcus marlatti Cockerell and its allies. United States Department of Agriculture Technical Bulletin, 404, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1934">Stickney (1934)</bibRefCitation>
and are apterous (
<figureCitation box="[423,505,1443,1470]" captionStart="FIGURE 57" captionStartId="141.[151,248,1587,1612]" captionTargetBox="[159,1432,185,1562]" captionTargetId="figure@141.[151,1436,181,1562]" captionTargetPageId="141" captionText="FIGURE 57. Phoenicococcus marlatti Cockerell. Apterous adult male. (Phoenicococcidae)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3774288/files/figure.png" pageId="140" pageNumber="141">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
